{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535539","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535539"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:56:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:56:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15486"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15486"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.09,0.08,0.77,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8177"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61576"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8177","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8177"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15486"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47029"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"316"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2117"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2443"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"3189"},{"type":"tags","id":"3310"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3806"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19804"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61576"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 77-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with three weeks of progressive lethargy, confusion, nausea with vomiting and unintentional weight loss. She has a medical history of ischaemic heart disease, atrial fibrillation, chronic kidney disease, osteoarthritis, and hypertension. Her medications include apixaban, metoprolol, perindopril, and paracetamol. She lives alone and has previously been independent with all activities of daily living.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 146/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. She is oriented to person only and has a Glasgow Coma Scale score of 14/15. Neurological examination reveals no unilateral limb weakness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECT imaging of the brain, chest, abdomen and pelvis reveals a 6 cm mass in the right upper lobe of the lung with multiple intracerebral metastases. There is significant oedema surrounding the metastases and midline shift of 8 mm.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Whole brain radiotherapy","Acetazolamide","Chemotherapy","High-dose dexamethasone","Haloperidol"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and signs of raised intracranial pressure secondary to multiple brain metastases from a likely primary lung cancer. The presence of confusion, lethargy, nausea, vomiting, and significant cerebral oedema with midline shift on imaging indicates urgent treatment is needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh-dose dexamethasone\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial management. It rapidly reduces perilesional oedema and improves neurological symptoms within 24-48 hours. For severe symptoms with significant mass effect, as in this case, the recommended starting dose is 16 mg daily in divided doses. The dose can be tapered based on clinical response over the following days. Due to possibility of gastric ulcer or haemorrhage, proton pump inhibitor or H2 antagonists should be used prophylactically.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWhole brain radiotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is an important treatment modality for multiple brain metastases but is not the first step. It is typically commenced after initial stabilisation with steroids and assessment of functional status, and is often given in conjunction with chemo/immunotherapy. The decision to proceed should consider the patient\u0027s overall prognosis and goals of care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcetazolamide\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated for the management of vasogenic oedema associated with brain metastases. While it can reduce cerebrospinal fluid production, it is more commonly used in conditions like idiopathic intracranial hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChemotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E or immunotherapy may be considered as part of a comprehensive oncological treatment plan but is not the appropriate initial management for acute raised intracranial pressure. The choice of systemic therapy would depend on tissue diagnosis and molecular profiling of the lung cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaloperidol\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered for managing agitation or delirium but does not address the underlying cause of raised intracranial pressure. Additionally, antipsychotics should be used cautiously in patients with brain metastases as they may lower the seizure threshold.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter initiating dexamethasone, the next steps would include early involvement of palliative care services, discussion of goals of care with the patient and family, and development of a comprehensive management plan that may include radiotherapy and systemic therapy as appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dexamethasone is the first-line treatment for symptomatic raised intracranial pressure from brain metastases.","The initial dexamethasone dose should be based on symptom severity, with higher doses (16mg daily) for severe symptoms.","Early involvement of palliative care services improves quality of life in patients with metastatic cancer."],"references":["Mitchell DK, Kwon HJ, Kubica PA, Huff WX, O\u2019regan R, Dey M. Brain metastases: An update on the multi-disciplinary approach of clinical management. Neurochirurgie. 2022 Jan 1;68(1):69-85. Available online at ; https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0028377021000990","Rabinstein AA. Treatment of cerebral edema. The neurologist. 2006 Mar 1;12(2):59-73. Available online at ; https://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/document?repid=rep1\u0026type=pdf\u0026doi=93edf7af7d76fc4108dd85c3008c0279d5d6a42e","Goldman M, Lucke-Wold B, Martinez-Sosa M, Katz J, Mehkri Y, Valisno J, Quintin S. Steroid utility, immunotherapy, and brain tumor management: an update on conflicting therapies. Exploration of Targeted Anti-tumor Therapy. 2022;3(5):659. Available online at ;  https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9630032/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47029"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15486"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47029","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47029"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-15T20:45:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-15T20:46:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8177"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61576"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"28","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/28"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc95","name":"Palliative Care","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"